ly a few sightings between 1981 and 1984, and a specimen collected in 1984. This specimen is now considered to have been a plumage aberration. A 2017 DNA analysis revealed that the bird(s) were common icterine greenbuls, albeit with unusual plumage colouring, which may have been caused by a nutritional deficiency. Alternative names for the Liberian greenbul included the spot-winged bulbul, spot-winged greenbul and white-winged greenbul. Distribution and habitat The icterine greenbul is found in Africa from Guinea to Ghana; southern Nigeria to western and southern Uganda, eastern and central Democratic Republic of the Congo and extreme north-western Angola. Its natural habitats are subtropical or tropical dry forests, subtropical or tropical moist lowland forests, and moist savanna. References Further reading Collinson, J.M.; Päckert, M.; Lawrie, Y.; Gatter, W.; Töpfer, T.; Phalan, B.; Fishpool, L. (2017). \"Taxonomic status of the Liberian Greenbul Phyllastrephus leucolepis and the conservation importance of the Cavalla Forest, Liberia\". Journal of Ornithology. 159: 19–27. doi:10.1007/s10336-017-1477-0. hdl:2164/8948. External links Image at ADW", "shortSummary": "The icterine greenbul (Phyllastrephus icterinus) is a species of songbird in the bulbul family, Pycnonotidae. It is native to the African t…", "locations": ["熱帶和亞熱帶濕潤闊葉林", "森林"], "habitats": ["稀树草原"], "imageUrl": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a1/Icterine_Greenbul_imported_from_iNaturalist_photo_225196965_on_4_September_2024_%28cropped%29.jpg/960px-Icterine_Greenbul_imported_from_iNaturalist_photo_225196965_on_4_September_2024_%28cropped%29.jpg", "kingdomId": "taxonomy-kingdom-animalia", "phylumId": "taxonomy-phylum-chordata", "classId": "taxonomy-class-aves", "genusId": "taxonomy-genus-phyllastrephus", "speciesId": "taxonomy-species-phyllastrephus-icterinus", "taxonomyIds": {"kingdom": "taxonomy-kingdom-animalia", "phylum": "taxonomy-phylum-chordata", "class": "taxonomy-class-ave